"Pereira de Lucena A.F., Szklo A.S., Schaeffer R., Dutra R.M.","The vulnerability of wind power to climate change in Brazil",2010,"Renewable Energy","35","5",,"904","912",,,10.1016/j.renene.2009.10.022,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-73549119463&partnerID=40&md5=72faa5a6507f8ca1e9a1c148a7e7d2a2","Energy Planning Program, Graduate School of Engineering, Federal University of Rio de Janeiro, Centro de Tecnologia, Bloco C, 21941-972 Ilha do Fundao, Rio de Janeiro, RJ, Brazil; Electric Power Research Center - CEPEL, P.O. Box 68007, 21944-970 Rio de Janeiro, RJ, Brazil","Pereira de Lucena, A.F., Energy Planning Program, Graduate School of Engineering, Federal University of Rio de Janeiro, Centro de Tecnologia, Bloco C, 21941-972 Ilha do Fundao, Rio de Janeiro, RJ, Brazil; Szklo, A.S., Energy Planning Program, Graduate School of Engineering, Federal University of Rio de Janeiro, Centro de Tecnologia, Bloco C, 21941-972 Ilha do Fundao, Rio de Janeiro, RJ, Brazil; Schaeffer, R., Energy Planning Program, Graduate School of Engineering, Federal University of Rio de Janeiro, Centro de Tecnologia, Bloco C, 21941-972 Ilha do Fundao, Rio de Janeiro, RJ, Brazil; Dutra, R.M., Electric Power Research Center - CEPEL, P.O. Box 68007, 21944-970 Rio de Janeiro, RJ, Brazil","The availability and reliability of wind power depend a great deal on current and future climate conditions, which may vary in light of possible global climate change (GCC). Long-term energy planning, however, does not normally take possible future GCC into consideration, which may turn out to be a risky exercise. In the case of Brazil, the untapped wind power potential is known to be impressive, provided that climate conditions remain the same over time. The focus of this study is to analyze some possible impacts of GCC on the wind power potential of Brazil, by simulating wind conditions associated with the IPCC A2 and B2 Scenarios. Results based on the HadCM3 general circulation model and the analysis of the country's wind database indicate that the wind power potential in Brazil would not be jeopardized in the future due to possible new climate conditions. On the contrary, improved wind conditions are expected, particularly in the Northeast coast of the country. Therefore, investments in wind power generation can be an interesting way to expand renewable energy production in Brazil. However, given the large uncertainties associated with GCC models and scenarios, the findings of this paper should be viewed as a possibility rather than as a projection. © 2009 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","Global climate change; Impacts; Wind power","Climate condition; Energy planning; Future climate; General circulation model; Global climate change; Global climate change impact; Global climate changes; On currents; Possible futures; Renewable energies; Wind conditions; Climate models; Electric power generation; Investments; Wind power; Climate change; climate change; climate effect; database; energy planning; global climate; Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change; investment; power generation; wind power; Brazil",,,,,,"MME, (2009) Balanço Energético Nacional 2009-Resultados Preliminares, , Empresa de Pesquisa Energética, Rio de Janeiro; (2001) Atlas do, , CEPEL, Potencial Eólico Brasileiro. Ed. CEPEL, Rio de Janeiro; Szklo, A.S., Geller, H., Policy options for sustainable energy development (2006) Brazil: a country profile on sustainable energy development, , IAEA (Ed), International Atomic Energy Agency, Vienna; Dutra, R.M., Szklo, A.S., Assessing long-term incentive programs for implementing wind power in Brazil using GIS rule-based methods (2008) Renewable Energy, 33, pp. 2507-2515; ANEEL, (2008) Banco de Informação de Geração, , http://www.aneel.gov.br/, Available at:, National Electricity Regulatory Agency [Accessed on March 2008]; Bittencourt, R.M., et al, Estabilização Sazonal da Oferta de Energia Através da Complementariedade entre os Regimes Hidrológico e